<DOC><DOCNO> AP880323-0161 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 1618EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Heard     03-23 0184</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Obit-Heard,0193</SECOND><HEAD>Centenarian Philanthropist Dies</HEAD><DATELINE>McKINNEY, Texas (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Bessie Heard, who endowed her hometownwith a wildlife sanctuary and natural science museum, has died, amuseum spokesman said Wednesday. She was 101.   More than 40,000 visitors each year come to the Heard NaturalScience Museum and Wildlife Sanctuary, which Miss Heard endowed in1964. It includes more than five miles of nature trails, said SteveRunnels, the museum's director of development.   The non-profit museum and sanctuary are funded by the BessieHeard Foundation, membership dues, tuition fees, gift shop salesand contributions.   At the heart of the museum was ``Miss Bessie,'' as she was knownfor most of her life.   Miss Heard died Tuesday night at home, Runnels said.   She was born May 26, 1886, the eldest of five daughters. Herfather, John Spencer Heard, spent four years in the ConfederateArmy and then opened a general store in McKinney, north of Dallas,with his brother.   Miss Heard attended Mary Baldwin College in Staunton, Va., butspent most of her life in McKinney.   Survivors include two cousins. A funeral was scheduled Friday.</TEXT></DOC>